The "real" reason that the idiot conspiracy theorists think the entire car should have melted like one of Dali's clocks isn't the heat of the sun as such.  It's the thermosphere.  For anyone who doesn't know, the thermosphere is the portion of earth's atmosphere that starts roughly at the border of space and goes up a few thousand miles.  (I don't remember what's quoted as the exact boundaries, but it's easy to look up.)  The atoms of the very thin atmosphere in this s area are accelerated to huge speeds by solar radiation.  This means that by the definition of temperature (mean kinetic energy), this area is very, VERY hot.  Easily hot enough to melt whatever the CTers say should melt.  EXCEPT.  Temperature is not the same thing as heat.  Heat -- the energy that makes things hot -- is transferred in three ways.  Radiation (direct from the sun, which at earth's radius is only enough to heat objects to a bit less than the earth's own mean temperature.  Let's say 0 degrees Celsius ballpark.)  Convection (mixing of mediums, not a factor here) and conduction (direct transfer of energy from one atom to another).  It's this last one that the CTers don't want to understand.  There are simply not enough of these fast-moving atoms around to transfer meaningful amounts of heat to anything.  To use a metaphor -- it's the difference between what happens to you if someone flings a drop of water at you once or twice a day, vs what would happen to you if the contents of a small lake got dumped on you all at once.
